+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016fJKMYDJYDpKX4EwwBjD11","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a comprehensive picture. Here is my full review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Full-Text Search Implementation\n\n### Summary\n\nAll 35 tests pass (20 search tests + 15 notes tests), the FTS5 virtual table and sync triggers are correctly structured, and the overall architecture is sound. However, there are several issues of varying severity -- most notably, the `sanitizeFtsQuery` function fails to handle FTS5 keyword operators (`OR`, `AND`, `NOT`), which will cause 500 errors in production when users type those words as search terms.\n\n---\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n- **Correct FTS5 content-sync table design.** The use of `content='notes'` and `content_rowid='id'` with the external content pattern is the canonical way to set up FTS5 in SQLite. This avoids data duplication while still allowing ranking and snippets.\n\n- **All three triggers (insert, update, delete) are correct.** The update trigger properly deletes the old row and inserts the new one -- this is the documented FTS5 pattern. The delete trigger uses the `INSERT INTO notes_fts(notes_fts, ...) VALUES('delete', ...)` command correctly.\n\n- **Parameterized queries throughout.** All SQL queries use `?` placeholders via `better-sqlite3`'s `.prepare()` API. There is no string interpolation into SQL. SQL injection is not possible here.\n\n- **BM25 ranking is correctly applied.** `ORDER BY bm25(notes_fts)` works because `bm25()` returns negative values (more negative = more relevant), so the default ascending sort correctly places the most relevant results first.\n\n- **Good test coverage.** The 20 test cases cover basic search, phrase matching, field validation, snippets, pagination, CRUD sync, special characters, and performance.\n\n---\n\n### Critical Issues (Must Fix)\n\n#### 1. FTS5 keyword operators pass through `sanitizeFtsQuery` and cause 500 errors\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 6-22\n\nThe sanitizer strips punctuation-based FTS5 syntax (`*`, `+`, `^`, `{`, `}`, `:`) but does **not** handle FTS5's keyword-based operators: `OR`, `AND`, `NOT`, and `NEAR`. When a user searches for any of these words (or any query that leaves a trailing/leading operator), the FTS5 `MATCH` expression throws `SqliteError`, which the error handler maps to a generic 500 Internal Server Error.\n\nConfirmed crash cases:\n- `q=OR` -- throws `fts5: syntax error near \"OR\"`\n- `q=NOT` -- throws `fts5: syntax error near \"NOT\"`\n- `q=test OR` -- throws `fts5: syntax error near \"\"`\n- `q=NOT NOT` -- throws `fts5: syntax error near \"NOT\"`\n\nThis means any user who searches for the word \"or\", \"and\", or \"not\" (FTS5 operators are case-insensitive) will get a 500 error.\n\n**Recommendation:** Wrap each standalone term in double quotes so FTS5 treats them as literal tokens, or explicitly strip/escape the keyword operators. The simplest robust approach:\n\n```typescript\nfunction sanitizeFtsQuery(q: string): string {\n  const phrases: string[] = [];\n  const withoutPhrases = q.replace(/\"([^\"]*)\"/g, (_match, inner) => {\n    if (inner.trim()) {\n      phrases.push(`\"${inner}\"`);\n    }\n    return '';\n  });\n  const cleanedTerms = withoutPhrases.replace(/[^a-zA-Z0-9\\s]/g, ' ').trim();\n  const parts = [...phrases];\n  if (cleanedTerms) {\n    // Quote each individual term to neutralize FTS5 keyword operators\n    const quotedTerms = cleanedTerms\n      .split(/\\s+/)\n      .filter(t => t.length > 0)\n      .map(t => `\"${t}\"`)\n      .join(' ');\n    parts.push(quotedTerms);\n  }\n  return parts.join(' ').trim();\n}\n```\n\nThis ensures `OR` becomes `\"OR\"`, `test OR` becomes `\"test\" \"OR\"`, and no bare keyword operators reach FTS5.\n\n#### 2. Suggest endpoint double-quotes already-quoted phrases, producing malformed FTS5 syntax\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, line 87\n\n```typescript\nconst prefixQuery = sanitized.split(/\\s+/).map(term => `\"${term}\"*`).join(' ');\n```\n\nWhen the input is `\"exact phrase\"`, `sanitizeFtsQuery` returns `\"exact phrase\"`. Then `.split(/\\s+/)` yields `['\"exact', 'phrase\"']`. The `.map(term => \\`\"${term}\"*\\`)` then produces `\"\\\"exact\"*` and `\"phrase\\\"\"*` -- nested/mismatched quotes that create malformed FTS5 syntax.\n\nWhile SQLite happens to not crash on this particular malformation (it silently misparses it), it does not produce the intended prefix search behavior. A phrase query input to the suggest endpoint will return unexpected or no results.\n\n**Recommendation:** Strip quotes from the sanitized string before building the prefix query, or restructure the suggest logic to handle phrases separately:\n\n```typescript\n// Strip existing quotes, then split and wrap each term for prefix matching\nconst stripped = sanitized.replace(/\"/g, '');\nconst prefixQuery = stripped.split(/\\s+/)\n  .filter(t => t.length > 0)\n  .map(term => `\"${term}\"*`)\n  .join(' ');\n```\n\n---\n\n### Important Issues (Should Fix)\n\n#### 3. Non-ASCII / Unicode characters are silently stripped\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, line 16\n\n```typescript\nconst cleanedTerms = withoutPhrases.replace(/[^a-zA-Z0-9\\s]/g, ' ').trim();\n```\n\nThe regex `[^a-zA-Z0-9\\s]` only allows ASCII letters and digits. Any accented characters (`cafe`), CJK characters, Cyrillic, Arabic, etc. are silently removed. A search for `cafe` returns results, but `cafe` (with the accent) returns an empty set rather than finding the same content.\n\nThis is a significant limitation for any internationalized dataset.\n\n**Recommendation:** Use a Unicode-aware character class:\n\n```typescript\nconst cleanedTerms = withoutPhrases.replace(/[^\\p{L}\\p{N}\\s]/gu, ' ').trim();\n```\n\nThis preserves all Unicode letters (`\\p{L}`) and numbers (`\\p{N}`) while stripping FTS5 operator characters.\n\n#### 4. Statements are re-prepared on every request\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 46-63 and 89-96\n\nBoth the search and suggest endpoints call `db.prepare(...)` inside the request handler on every invocation. While `better-sqlite3` caches prepared statements internally, this adds needless overhead. The prepared statements are static SQL and should be created once.\n\n**Recommendation:** Prepare statements once at route creation time:\n\n```typescript\nexport function createRoutes(db: Database.Database): Router {\n  const router = Router();\n\n  const countStmt = db.prepare(`\n    SELECT COUNT(*) as total FROM notes_fts WHERE notes_fts MATCH ?\n  `);\n  const searchStmt = db.prepare(`\n    SELECT notes.id, notes.title,\n      snippet(notes_fts, 1, '<mark>', '</mark>', '...', 32) as snippet,\n      bm25(notes_fts) as rank\n    FROM notes_fts JOIN notes ON notes.id = notes_fts.rowid\n    WHERE notes_fts MATCH ?\n    ORDER BY bm25(notes_fts)\n    LIMIT ? OFFSET ?\n  `);\n  const suggestStmt = db.prepare(`\n    SELECT notes.id, notes.title\n    FROM notes_fts JOIN notes ON notes.id = notes_fts.rowid\n    WHERE notes_fts MATCH ?\n    ORDER BY bm25(notes_fts)\n    LIMIT 5\n  `);\n\n  // ... use these in handlers\n```\n\n#### 5. FTS5 errors surface as 500 instead of 400\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/errors.ts`, lines 19-33\n\nEven after fixing the sanitizer, there is no defense-in-depth. If an FTS5 `MATCH` expression somehow still fails (e.g., a future regression in the sanitizer), the `SqliteError` propagates to the generic error handler, which returns a 500 with `\"Internal server error\"`. For a malformed search query, a 400 with a descriptive message would be far more appropriate.\n\n**Recommendation:** Catch `SqliteError` specifically in the search handlers, or add a check in the error handler:\n\n```typescript\n// In the search route catch block, or error handler:\nif (err instanceof Database.SqliteError && err.message.includes('fts5:')) {\n  res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid search query' });\n  return;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Suggestions (Nice to Have)\n\n#### 6. `perPage` is hardcoded with no client control\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, line 36\n\nThe page size is fixed at 20. Consider accepting an optional `perPage` query parameter with a capped maximum (e.g., max 100) to give API consumers more flexibility:\n\n```typescript\nconst perPage = Math.min(Math.max(1, parseInt(req.query.perPage as string) || 20), 100);\n```\n\n#### 7. Response types are not explicitly typed\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/routes.ts`\n\nThe code defines `SearchResult` and `SuggestResult` interfaces in `/workspace/src/models.ts` (lines 16-26), but the route handlers never reference them. The `results` arrays sent in responses are untyped `any[]`. Adding explicit typing would improve maintainability:\n\n```typescript\nconst results = searchStmt.all(sanitized, perPage, offset) as SearchResult[];\n```\n\n#### 8. The `total` count query is a separate round-trip\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/routes.ts`, lines 46-49\n\nThe total count is computed with a separate FTS5 `MATCH` query, which duplicates the search work. For large datasets, this doubles the FTS scan time. An alternative pattern is to use a CTE or `COUNT(*) OVER()` window function in a single query, though with SQLite's FTS5, the separate query approach is the most common pattern and is acceptable for moderate-scale data.\n\n#### 9. Missing test for FTS5 keyword operator queries\n\n**File:** `/workspace/tests/search.test.ts`\n\nThe special-characters test (test 19, line 206) covers URL-encoded punctuation but does not test searches for `OR`, `AND`, `NOT`, or `NEAR` -- the exact inputs that currently crash the server. Adding a test case would have caught Critical Issue #1:\n\n```typescript\nit('FTS5 keyword operators in query do not crash', async () => {\n  const operatorQueries = ['OR', 'AND', 'NOT', 'test OR', 'NOT NOT', 'NEAR'];\n  for (const q of operatorQueries) {\n    const res = await request(appCtx.app).get(`/notes/search?q=${encodeURIComponent(q)}`);\n    expect(res.status).toBe(200);\n    expect(Array.isArray(res.body.results)).toBe(true);\n  }\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### Issue Summary Table\n\n| # | Severity | Location | Issue |\n|---|----------|----------|-------|\n| 1 | **Critical** | `/workspace/src/routes.ts:6-22` | FTS5 keyword operators (`OR`, `AND`, `NOT`) pass through sanitizer and cause 500 errors |\n| 2 | **Critical** | `/workspace/src/routes.ts:87` | Suggest endpoint double-quotes phrases, producing malformed FTS5 syntax |\n| 3 | **Important** | `/workspace/src/routes.ts:16` | Non-ASCII characters silently stripped from search queries |\n| 4 | **Important** | `/workspace/src/routes.ts:46-63,89-96` | Prepared statements re-created on every request |\n| 5 | **Important** | `/workspace/src/errors.ts:19-33` | FTS5 errors return 500 instead of 400 |\n| 6 | Suggestion | `/workspace/src/routes.ts:36` | `perPage` is hardcoded; no client control |\n| 7 | Suggestion | `/workspace/src/routes.ts:46-64,89-97` | Response arrays not typed with `SearchResult`/`SuggestResult` |\n| 8 | Suggestion | `/workspace/src/routes.ts:46-49` | Separate COUNT query duplicates FTS5 scan |\n| 9 | Suggestion | `/workspace/tests/search.test.ts` | No test for FTS5 keyword operator queries |\n\nThe two critical issues (#1 and #2) should be addressed before merging. Issue #1 in particular is a production-facing bug -- any user who types \"or\", \"and\", or \"not\" into the search box will receive a 500 error."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a0066f1 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 36267\ntool_uses: 17\nduration_ms: 190419</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"337462a2-9445-47f8-b33b-23f85d1a74c0","uuid":"fb74ab5e-ca50-4122-bae9-daa889c6a85b","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the changes made to implement full-text search in this Express + SQLite note-taking API. The changes are in:\n- /workspace/src/db.ts (added FTS5 vi